.TH CMP(1),User Commands,CMP(1)

.SH NAME
cmp - compare two files byte by byte

.SH SYNOPSIS
cmp [-lsh] [--] file1 file2

.SH DESCRIPTION
cmp reads file1 and file2 one byte at a time and reports the first position at which they differ.
A filename of - reads from standard input.

With no options, cmp prints a message of the form "file1 file2 differ: char N, line M" at the first differing byte and exits 1.
If one file is a prefix of the other, cmp prints "EOF on FILE after byte N" and exits 1.
If the files are identical, cmp exits 0 with no output.

.SH OPTIONS
-l: Print each pair of differing bytes as "byte-number octal1 octal2" and continue comparing rather than stopping at the first difference.

-s: Silent. Suppress all output; only the exit status indicates the result.

-h: Print a brief usage summary and exit 0.

--: End of options. Subsequent arguments are treated as filenames even if they begin with -.

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: Files are identical.

1: Files differ or one is a prefix of the other.

2: Invalid usage, missing filename, or failure to open a file.

.SH EXAMPLES
Quiet check (exit status only):

$ cmp -s a.bin b.bin

Report every differing byte:

$ cmp -l a.bin b.bin
